                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a/392a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-12T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 12, 1929—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>294. The Secretary of State handed the Japanese Ambassador an <hi rend="italic"
                        >aide-mémoire</hi> this noon concerning the Japanese desires at the
                    forthcoming naval conference which reads as follows:</p>
                <p>[Here follows the text of the <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> printed <hi
                        rend="italic">supra.</hi>]</p>
                <p>You may communicate a copy of the <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> to the
                    Prime Minister for his confidential information.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
